 monarchical ideology is to be found in the popular literary genre known as the Jātakas, tales of the Buddha's past lives. The best-known of these, the Vessantara Jātaka, disseminated an ideal of an infinitely generous prince as a bodhisatta or future Buddha—an ideal which remains influential in Thailand today. Using primary and secondary source materials largely unknown in Western scholarship, Jory traces the history of the Vessantara Jātaka and its political-cultural importance from the ancient to the modern period. Although pressures from European colonial powers and Buddhist reformers led eventually to a revised political conception of the monarchy, the older Buddhist ideal of kingship has yet endured.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBuddhism and statexHistoryxThailand. 0aBuddhism and statezThailandxHistory. 0aMonarchyxHistoryxThailand. 0aMonarchyzThailandxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846090140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438460901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438460901/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles